                        <outline text="Problem Description.">
                            <outline text="Scenario 1.">
<outline text="Priority Ranking for Software Vulnerability Patching">
    <outline text="This is a historical report on a scenario, taking place in 2019."/>
    <outline text="Alan is in charge of vulnerability management for the IT systems of his company. The security policy of his organisation only allows for critical patching of one software per day, due to issues with bandwidth and system downtime during the patching process. #level1 #level2 "/>
    <outline text="Today, he has discovered that the Checkpoint Gateway, deployed for connecting approximately 400 employee desktop machines to the internet, has an unpatched vulnerability $$v_1$$ which was released in October this year. #level1 #level2 "/>
    <outline text="Furthermore, he receives an alert that the not more specified vulnerability $$v_2$$, identified as `CVE-2018-8626`, is present on his system. #level1 #level2 "/>
    <outline text="He is also worried about several vulnerabilities in Adobe Acrobat and Reader which have been published last month. This software suite is used by a small team of 10 employees. #level1 #level2 "/>
    <outline text="Which software should he patch today? And which one tomorrow?"/>
</outline>
                            </outline>
                            <outline text="Solution.">
<outline text="He needs to decide on the order in which he should patch these vulnerabilities. He can use online information to determine the severity of the different vulnerabilities. #level1">
    <outline text="Step 1: For each vulnerability, find out its CVSS score and note the precise software version affected. #level2">
        <outline text="Vulnerability $$v_1$$:">
            <outline text="https://nvd.nist.gov/vuln/detail/CVE-2019-8461"/>
            <outline text="Check Point Endpoint Security Initial Client for Windows before version E81.30 tries to load a DLL placed in any PATH location on a clean image without Endpoint Client installed. An attacker can leverage this to gain LPE using a specially crafted DLL placed in any PATH location accessible with write permissions to the user."/>
            <outline text="Base Score: [7.8 HIGH](https://nvd.nist.gov/vuln-metrics/cvss/v3-calculator?name=CVE-2019-8461&amp;vector=AV:L/AC:L/PR:N/UI:R/S:U/C:H/I:H/A:H&amp;version=3.0&amp;source=NIST)"/>
            <outline text="Vector:  `CVSS:3.0/AV:L/AC:L/PR:N/UI:R/S:U/C:H/I:H/A:H`"/>
        </outline>
        <outline text="Vulnerability $$v_2$$: ">
            <outline text="According to https://nvd.nist.gov/vuln/detail/CVE-2018-8626 :"/>
            <outline text="A remote code execution vulnerability exists in Windows Domain Name System (DNS) servers when they fail to properly handle requests, aka &quot;Windows DNS Server Heap Overflow Vulnerability.&quot; This affects Windows Server 2012 R2, Windows Server 2019, Windows Server 2016, Windows 10, Windows 10 Servers."/>
            <outline text="Base Score: [9.8 CRITICAL](https://nvd.nist.gov/vuln-metrics/cvss/v3-calculator?name=CVE-2018-8626&amp;vector=AV:N/AC:L/PR:N/UI:N/S:U/C:H/I:H/A:H&amp;version=3.0&amp;source=NIST)"/>
            <outline text="Vector:  `CVSS:3.0/AV:N/AC:L/PR:N/UI:N/S:U/C:H/I:H/A:H`"/>
            <outline text="So the software affected by the second vulnerability is a Windows DNS Server."/>
        </outline>
        <outline text="Vulnerability $$v_3$$:">
            <outline text="Which of the Acrobat software vulnerabilities is most critical?"/>
            <outline text="There are a lot of vulnerabilities but the most critical score is as in https://nvd.nist.gov/vuln/detail/CVE-2019-8237 :">
                <outline text="Base Score: [9.8 CRITICAL](https://nvd.nist.gov/vuln-metrics/cvss/v3-calculator?name=CVE-2019-8237&amp;vector=AV:N/AC:L/PR:N/UI:N/S:U/C:H/I:H/A:H&amp;version=3.1&amp;source=NIST)"/>
                <outline text="Vector:  `CVSS:3.1/AV:N/AC:L/PR:N/UI:N/S:U/C:H/I:H/A:H`"/>
            </outline>
        </outline>
    </outline>
    <outline text="Step 2: Compare and rank all the scores. #level2 ">
        <outline text="We find: $$\mu(v_1)=7.8$$, $$\mu(v_2)=9.8$$ and $$\mu(v_3)=9.8$$."/>
        <outline text="The first vulnerabiliy seems less severe, however access control for 400 employees depends on it."/>
        <outline text=" ![Pasted image](https://dynalist.io/u/TUdOKqz9W1rMud87atCAYEqv) "/>
    </outline>
    <outline text="Step 3: Patch the vulnerability with the highest score. #level2 "/>
</outline>
                            </outline>
                            <outline text="Wrap-Up."/>
                            <outline text="Scenario 2.">
<outline text="Heartbleed Bug and CVSS">
    <outline text="Through this exercise, you will better understand CVSS by studying the famous Heartbleed Bug. "/>
    <outline text="(a) Research the famous Heartbleed vulnerability. Find its CVE.">
        <outline text="CVE: `CVE-2014-0160`"/>
    </outline>
    <outline text="(b) Also find its CVSS v2 score (both numerical and string representation).">
        <outline text="CVSS v2.0 Severity and Metrics:">
            <outline text="Base Score: 5.0 MEDIUM"/>
            <outline text="Vector: `(AV:N/AC:L/Au:N/C:P/I:N/A:N)` (V2 legend)">
                <outline text="Exploitability Subscore: 10.0">
                    <outline text="Access Vector (AV): Network"/>
                    <outline text="Access Complexity (AC): Low"/>
                    <outline text="Authentication (AU): None"/>
                </outline>
                <outline text="Impact Subscore: 2.9">
                    <outline text="Confidentiality (C): Partial"/>
                    <outline text="Integrity (I): None"/>
                    <outline text="Availability (A): None"/>
                </outline>
                <outline text="Additional Information:"/>
                <outline text="Allows unauthorized disclosure of information"/>
            </outline>
        </outline>
        <outline text="String representation:">
            <outline text="`(AV:N/AC:L/Au:N/C:P/I:N/A:N)`. "/>
        </outline>
    </outline>
    <outline text="(c) Briefly sketch the meaning of the components in this vector notation and judge the credibility of this score, based on what you have learned in your research about Heartbleed.">
        <outline text="For example:">
            <outline text="AV:N -- The access vector is through the network."/>
            <outline text="C:P -- confidentiality is partially impacted upon. "/>
        </outline>
        <outline text="The Score of 5.0 seems somewhat low for this severe vulnerability."/>
    </outline>
    <outline text="(d) Now compare this with the v3 CVSS score of this vulnerability and interpret your findings. "/>
</outline>
