<outline text="Add your VM to your organisation's network by setting a static IP address. ">
    <outline text="Open a terminal and type the following:">
        <outline text="`sudo nano /etc/network/interfaces`"/>
    </outline>
    <outline text="The interfaces configuration file that you are editing, should be modified to include a unique IP address and an appropriate gateway address, for your VM. Initially the file is:">
        <outline text="`# This file describes the network interfaces available on your system and how to activate them. For more information, see interfaces(5).`"/>
        <outline text=""/>
        <outline text="`# The loopback network interface`"/>
        <outline text="`auto lo`"/>
        <outline text="`iface lo inet loopback`"/>
        <outline text=""/>
        <outline text="`# The primary network interface`"/>
        <outline text="`auto eth0`"/>
        <outline text="`iface eth0 inet dhcp`"/>
    </outline>
    <outline text="Edit the last line of this file by changing `dhcp` to `static`, resulting in">
        <outline text="`iface eth0 inet static`"/>
    </outline>
    <outline text="and append the following values that are appropriate for you organisations network:">
        <outline text="`address 192.168.3.xyz`"/>
        <outline text="`netmask 255.255.255.0`"/>
        <outline text="#`network 192.168.0.0`"/>
        <outline text="`gateway 192.168.3.1`"/>
    </outline>
</outline>
<outline text="Shutdown and restart the VM to boot with the new IP addess."/>
