                    <outline text="Authentication Protocols #h1  CI7130 #workshop ">
                        <outline text="The basic authentication scheme discussed in the lecture has some weaknesses. In particular, (A1) password guessing attacks, (A2) rainbow table or other pre-image attacks on hash functions, (A3) replay and (A4) man-in-the-middle attacks are all threatening the scheme. In this exercise, we will see how we can address at least some of these attacks. "/>
                        <outline text="(a) Why does sending $$h(user || pwd)$$, where user is the unique username and pwd the password of Alice, make attack A1 (and A2) more difficult? ">
                            <outline text="Since there should now be no duplicates in the password file anymore, it would make it more difficult for someone who has access to the password file, to guess the password. #item  #answer "/>
                            <outline text="It would also make a dictionary attack on the server more difficult as weak passwords containing dictionary words, are not the sole input to the hash function anymore. #item #answer "/>
                        </outline>
                        <outline text="(b) Now consider the following more sophisticated authentication scheme:">
                            <outline text="The server initiates by sending a random value $$N_S$$. #item  "/>
                            <outline text="Client Alice responds by sending $$h(h(user || pwd) || N_S)$$ and $$N_S$$. #item  "/>
                            <outline text="Server checks whether he can compute the first hash digest value, and checks the integrity of $$N_S$$. #item  "/>
                        </outline>
                        <outline text="Against which attacks (A1-A4) does this protect, and why? Which attacks does it not address? Hint: check out RFC 2069, available on the Internet. ">
                            <outline text="This uses a server nonce in order to strengthen the protocol. This makes attacks A1 and A2 even more difficult due to additional randomness in the input of the hash function. It also helps to prevent replay attacks A3 on the protocol since each client reply is now unique to each transaction and hence not valid, if it was replayed from a previous session. #answer  "/>
                            <outline text="However, a man-in-the-middle attack A4 is still possible, provided the man in the middle captures all the different requests and responses. #answer  "/>
                        </outline>
                    </outline>
                    <outline text="Peer-to-peer Technology for Mobile Learning #master #CI7160 #workshop " _note="#level1 #level2 #solution">
                        <outline text="Read the following description of a fictitious case study, and answer the questions below."/>
                        <outline text="A university uses peer-to-peer technology in order to enable the sharing of electronic documents of students, participating in an interactive tutorial session, using their smartphones. In order to join the session, students use an app on their mobile phone, which set up the security scheme. Each student will need to use public key cryptography in order to send confidential messages to other users, and to digitally (authenticate) messages sent from their phones."/>
                        <outline text="Consider a scenario, where each student is required to create a public and private key when enrolling at the University, and to upload the public key to a central repository. An appropriate key management protocol retrieves the public key whenever needed. Discuss advantages and disadvantages of the scheme, when considering the context of the case study.">
                            <outline text="Hint: in order to proceed with your discussion for this scenario, you may ask yourself some questions, following the standard security assessment methodology.">
<outline text="What are the crucial assets in this scenario?">
