<outline text="This lab requires pre-built SEEDUbuntu VM. For the Cyberlab users, use the command create_vm.sh. to open this VM. For Azurelab users, you can get this VM in the virtualbox."/>
<outline text="For Azurelab users,  go to      https://labs.azure.com/virtualmachines) for which the username is kingston and password is DemoTo login to the SEEDUbuntu VM, the username is seed and password is dees in case you will be asked. In this lab, we will use openssl commands and libraries. We have already installed OpenSSL binaries in our VMs."/>
<outline text="In this lab, we need to create digital certificates, but we are not going to pay any commercial CA. We will become a root CA ourselves, and then use this CA to issue the certificate for others (e.g. servers). In this task, we will make ourselves a root CA, and generate a certificate for this CA. Unlike other certificates, which are usually signed by another CA, the root CA’s certificates are self-signed. Root CA’s certificates are usually pre-loaded into most operating systems, web browsers, and other software that rely on PKI. Root CA’s certificates are unconditionally trusted."/>
<outline text="The Configuration File openssl.conf:    In order to use OpenSSL to create certificates, you have to have a configuration file. The configuration file usually has an extension .cnf. It is used by three OpenSSL commands: ca, req and xThe manual page of openssl.conf can be found online. You can also get a copy of the configuration file from /usr/lib/ssl/openssl.cnf. Open a new directory on your name which will be the current directory, or you can work on the existing /home/seed directorry. You need to copy openssl.cnf file in this directory.  After copying this file into your current directory, you need to create several sub-directories as specified in the configuration file (look at the [CA_default] section):"/>
<outline text="dir = ./demoCA     # Where everything is kept certs = $dir/certs    # Where the issued certs are kept crl_dir = $dir/crl    # Where the issued crl are kept new_certs_dir = $dir/newcerts  # default place for new certs. database = $dir/index.txt   # database index file."/>
<outline text="serial = $dir/serial            # The current serial number"/>
<outline text="For the index.txt file, simply create an empty file. For the serial file, put a single number in string format (e.g. 1000) in the file. Once you have set up the configuration file openssl.cnf, you can create and issue certificates."/>
<outline text="Note: You will need a basic Linux command to perform this task or other tasks in the lab. For example, cd, cp, mkdir, touch, echo, nano, ls, cd../, pwd etc. Please be familiar with them before proceeding further. You need to come to your current directory (your name) to complete the rest of the tasks."/>
<outline text="Certificate Authority (CA). As we described before, we need to generate a self-signed certificate for our CA. This means that this CA is totally trusted, and its certificate will serve as the root certificate. You can run the following command to generate the self-signed certificate for the CA:"/>
<outline text="$ openssl req -new -x509 -keyout ca.key -out ca.crt -config openssl.cnf"/>
<outline text="You will be prompted for information and a password. You need to note this password because you will have to type this each time you want to use this CA to sign certificates for others. I recommend selecting the same password for each task just to avoid any confusion. You will also be asked to fill in some information, such as the Country Name (2 byte or two letters only), Common Name, etc., which you need to keep in the record so that you can use then for certificate signing request.  The output of the command is stored in two files: ca.key and ca.crt. The file ca.key contains the CA’s private key, while ca.crt contains the public-key certificate."/>
<outline text="QWhat are the key components that you found in the digital certificate? Discuss with examples."/>
<outline text="Task 2: Create a Certificate for KUCyberlab2021.com"/>
<outline text="Now, we become a root CA, we are ready to sign digital certificates for our customers. Our first customer is a company called KUCyberlab2021.com. For this company to get a digital certificate from a CA, it needs to go through three steps."/>
<outline text="Step 1: Generate a public/private key pair.  The company needs to first create its own public/private key pair. We can run the following command to generate an RSA key pair (both private and public keys). You will also be required to provide a password to encrypt the private key (using the AES-128 encryption algorithm, as is specified in the command option). The keys will be stored in the file server.key:"/>
<outline text="$ openssl genrsa -aes128 -out server.key 1024"/>
<outline text="QWhat does 1024 indicate in this command? Also, mention the purpose of the password you entered in this state in terms of cryptographic algorithms."/>
<outline text="The server.key is an encoded text file (also encrypted), so you will not be able to see the actual content, such as the modulus, private exponents, etc. To see those, you can run the following command:"/>
<outline text="$ openssl rsa -in server.key -text"/>
<outline text="QWhat parameters can you get (related to cryptographic algorithms) in the server.key file."/>
<outline text="Step 2: Generate a Certificate Signing Request (CSR).  Once the company has the key file, it should generate a Certificate Signing Request (CSR), which basically includes the company’s public key. The CSR will be sent to the CA, who will generate a certificate for the key (usually after ensuring that identity information in the CSR matches with the server’s true identity). Please use KUCyberlab2021.com as the common name of the certificate request. Other client information should be the same as previously mentioned while configuring CA."/>
<outline text="$ openssl req -new -key server.key -out server.csr -config openssl.cnf"/>
<outline text="It should be noted that the above command is quite similar to the one we used in creating the selfsigned certificate for the CA. The only difference is the -x509 option. Without it, the command generates a request; with it, the command generates a self-signed certificate."/>
<outline text="Step 3: Generating Certificates. The CSR file needs to have the CA’s signature to form a certificate. In the real world, the CSR files are usually sent to a trusted CA for their signature. In this lab, we will use our own trusted CA to generate certificates. The following command turns the certificate signing request (server.csr) into an X509 certificate (server.crt), using the CA’s ca.crt and ca.key:"/>
<outline text="$ openssl ca -in server.csr -out server.crt -cert ca.crt  -keyfile ca.key \-config openssl.cnf"/>
<outline text="If OpenSSL refuses to generate certificates, it is very likely that the names in your requests do not match with those of CA. The matching rules are specified in the configuration file (look at the [policy_match] section). You can change the names of your requests to comply with the policy, or you can change the policy. The configuration file also includes another policy (called policy_anything), which is less restrictive."/>
<outline text="You can choose that policy by changing the following line:"/>
<outline text="&quot;policy = policy_match&quot; change to &quot;policy = policy_anything&quot;."/>
<outline text="QIn server.crt certificate file, what cryptographic algorithms did you find? Explain."/>
<outline text="1.1    Task 3: Deploying Certificates in an HTTPS Web Server"/>
<outline text="In this lab, we will explore how public-key certificates are used by websites to secure web browsing. We will set up an HTTPS website using openssl’s built-in web server."/>
<outline text="Step 1: Configuring DNS. We choose KUCyberlab2021.com as the name of our website. To get our computers to recognize this name, let us add the following entry to /etc/hosts; this entry basically maps the hostname KUCyberlab2021.com to our localhost (i.e., 127.0.0.1):"/>
<outline text="127.0.0.1  KUCyberlab2021.com"/>
<outline text="Step 2: Configuring the webserver. Let us launch a simple web server with the certificate generated in the previous task. OpenSSL allows us to start a simple web server using the s server command:">
    <outline text="Combine the secret key and certificate into one file"/>
</outline>
<outline text="$ cp server.key server.pem"/>
<outline text="$ cat server.crt &gt;&gt; server.pem">
    <outline text="Launch the webserver using server.pem"/>
</outline>
<outline text="$ openssl s_server -cert server.pem -www"/>
<outline text="By default, the server will listen on port You can alter that using the -accept option. Now, you can access the server using the following URL: https://KUCyberlab2021.com:4433/. Most likely, you will get an error message from the browser. In Firefox, you will see a message like the following: “KUCyberlab2021.com:4433 uses an invalid security certificate. The certificate is not trusted because the issuer certificate is unknown”."/>
<outline text="QTake the snapshot and explain the result."/>
<outline text="Step 3: Getting the browser to accept our CA certificate. Had our certificate been assigned by DigiCert or VeriSign, we will not have such an error message, because their certificate is very likely preloaded into Firefox’s certificate repository already. Unfortunately, the certificate of KUCyberlab2021.com is signed by our own CA (i.e., using ca.crt), and this CA is not recognized by Firefox. There are two ways to get Firefox to accept our CA’s self-signed certificate."/>
<outline text="•    We can request Mozilla (or Google) to include our CA’s certificate in its Firefox (or Chrome) software, so everybody using Firefox/Chrome can recognize our CA. This is how the real CAs, such as VeriSign and DigiCert, get their certificates into Firefox/Chrome. Unfortunately, our own CA does not have a large enough market for Mozilla/Google to include our certificate, so we will not pursue this direction."/>
<outline text="•    Load ca.crt into Firefox: We can manually add our CA’s certificate to the Firefox browser by clicking the following menu sequence:"/>
<outline text="Edit -&gt; Preference -&gt; Privacy &amp; Security -&gt; View Certificates."/>
<outline text="You will see a list of certificates that are already accepted by Firefox. From here, we can “import” our own certificate. Please import ca.crt, and select the following option: “Trust this CA to identify web sites”. You will see that our CA’s certificate is now in Firefox’s list of the accepted certificates."/>
<outline text="Step Testing our HTTPS website. Now, point the browser to https://"/>
<outline text="KUCyberlab2021.com:Please describe and explain your observations. Please also do the following tasks:"/>
<outline text="QTurn the server off and load the page. What do you find? Explain."/>
<outline text="Q Make a copy of server.pem as server1.pem so that you can restore it later. Modify a single byte of server.pem, and restart the server, and reload the URL. What do you observe? Make sure you restore the original server.pem afterwards. Note that the server may not be able to restart if certain places of server.pem are corrupted; in that case, choose another place to modify, e.g., private key, certificate values, expire date etc."/>
<outline text="QSince KUCyberlab2021.com points to the localhost, if we use https://localhost:4433 instead, we will be connecting to the same web server. Please do so, describe and explain your observations."/>
<outline text="1.2    Task 4: Deploying Certificate in an Apache-based HTTPS Website"/>
<outline text="The HTTPS server setup using openssl’s s_server command is primarily for debugging and demonstration purposes. In this lab, we set up a real HTTPS web server based on Apache. The Apache server, which is already installed in our VM, supports the HTTPS protocol. To create an HTTPS website, we just need to configure the Apache server, so it knows where to get the private key and certificates. An example is given in the following to show how to enable HTTPS for a website www.example.com. Your task is to do the same for KUCyberlab2021.com using the certificate generated from previous tasks."/>
<outline text="An Apache server can simultaneously host multiple websites. It needs to know the directory where a website’s files are stored. This is done via its VirtualHost file, located in the /etc/apache2/ sites-available directory. To add an HTTP website, we add a VirtualHost entry to the file 000-default.conf. See the following example."/>
<outline text="&lt;VirtualHost *:80&gt;"/>
<outline text="ServerName KUCyberlab2021.com"/>
<outline text="DocumentRoot /var/www/Example_One"/>
<outline text="DirectoryIndex index.html"/>
<outline text="&lt;/VirtualHost&gt;"/>
<outline text="To add an HTTPS website, we need to add a VirtualHost entry to the default-ssl.conf file in the same folder. Always use the sudo mode to modify the system files in Seed Ubuntu."/>
<outline text="&lt;VirtualHost *:443&gt;"/>
<outline text="ServerName KUCyberlab2021.com"/>
<outline text="DocumentRoot /var/www/Example_Two"/>
<outline text="DirectoryIndex index.html"/>
<outline text="SSLEngine On"/>
<outline text="SSLCertificateFile /etc/apache2/ssl/example_cert"/>
<outline text="SSLCertificateKeyFile /etc/apache2/ssl/example_key"/>
<outline text="&lt;/VirtualHost&gt;"/>
<outline text="The ServerName entry specifies the name of the website, while the DocumentRoot entry specifies where the files for the website are stored. The above example sets up the HTTPS site"/>
<outline text="https://two.example.com (port 443 is the default HTTPS port). First find the required certificate key key files to be stored in Apache. In the setup, we need to tell Apache where the server certificate (example_cert) and private key (example_key) are stored."/>
<outline text="After the default-ssl.conf file is modified, we need to run a series of commands to enable SSL. Apache will ask us to type the password used for encrypting the private key. Once everything is set up properly, we can browse the web site, and all the traffic between the browser and the server will be encrypted."/>
<outline text="// Test the Apache configuration file for errors"/>
<outline text="$ sudo apachectl configtest"/>
<outline text="// Enable the SSL module"/>
<outline text="$ sudo a2enmod ssl"/>
<outline text="// Enable the site we have just edited"/>
<outline text="$ sudo a2ensite default-ssl"/>
<outline text="// Restart Apache"/>
<outline text="$ sudo service apache2 restart"/>
<outline text="Please use the above example as guidance to set up an HTTPS server for KUCyberlab2021.com."/>
