                    <outline text="Managing Passwords #auth-PG CI7130 #workshop ">
                        <outline text="This exercise will give you some ideas how to find the scheme for managing your passwords."/>
                        <outline text="1. Review all the passwords you have to maintain for your own use. Group these passwords into categories, for example `personal`, `study`, `work` etc. ">
                            <outline text="Try to not have too many categories, around 5 is probably a good number. Write down your categories. Also, note the user accounts that fall into the categories (based on your initial passwords, do not write down these passwords however). You might find that you cannot remember the exact username anymore. Try to look them up/reconstruct them, and write them down."/>
                        </outline>
                        <outline text="2. For each category, devise a catchphrase. ">
                            <outline text="Remember that a catchphrase is a sentence in natural language, easy to remember. You should not feel that you have the need to write this down or store it in a password-protected file. In order to make this feasible, relate catchphrases to their specific category. So for example, a catchphrase for your `personal` category could be `I'm grateful for life!`."/>
                        </outline>
                        <outline text="3. Now design a scheme how to derive a password from a catchphrase. ">
                            <outline text="The scheme should depend on the specific user account name that requires the corresponding password. ">
<outline text="For example, your scheme could be to omit vowels from the catchphrase, add the characters `$` and `*`, followed by the last character of the username (this will make it specific for each account)."/>
                            </outline>
                        </outline>
                        <outline text="4. Apply your scheme to all your user accounts. ">
                            <outline text="This should, in most cases, give you passwords that are all different and that you do not need to write down. "/>
                            <outline text="Provided you remember the catchphrase and your scheme, you will always be able to reconstruct the passwords if required. This scheme certainly works very well for me!"/>
                        </outline>
                        <outline text="5. What might be restrictions of this scheme?">
                            <outline text="Server admin requirements such as password changes or prescribed patterns to enforce &quot;strong&quot; passwords. "/>
                        </outline>
